# Quran.co.in Architecture & Coding Principles

## Core Principles

### 1. Modularity & Component Structure
- **VERY MODULAR ARCHITECTURE**: Every component, utility, and module must be highly modular
- Each component should have a single, well-defined responsibility
- Components should be reusable and composable
- Follow a clear component hierarchy and structure
- Separate concerns: UI components, business logic, data access, utilities

### 2. SOLID Principles
- **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)**: Each class/function/component should have only one reason to change
- **Open/Closed Principle**: Open for extension, closed for modification
- **Liskov Substitution Principle**: Derived classes must be substitutable for their base classes
- **Interface Segregation Principle**: Many client-specific interfaces are better than one general-purpose interface
- **Dependency Inversion Principle**: Depend on abstractions, not concretions

### 3. File Size & Code Organization
- **MAXIMUM 300 LINES PER FILE**: If a file exceeds 300 lines, it MUST be refactored into smaller, focused modules
- Split large files into multiple smaller files with clear responsibilities
- Use barrel exports (index.ts) to organize related modules
- Group related functionality together

### 4. Data Structures
- **Use appropriate data structures**: Don't default to arrays everywhere
- Use **Hash Maps/Objects/Map** when you need:
  - Fast lookups by key
  - Unique key-value pairs
  - O(1) access time
- Use **Arrays** only when:
  - Order matters
  - You need sequential access
  - Duplicates are allowed and order is important
- Use **Sets** for unique collections
- Choose the right data structure for the problem

### 5. File Creation Workflow
- **ALWAYS CREATE FILES BEFORE WRITING CODE**: To avoid tool timeout issues
- Create empty files or file stubs first
- Then populate them with code
- This ensures proper file structure and prevents timeouts

### 6. Refactoring-Friendly Code
- Write code with future refactoring in mind
- Use clear, descriptive names
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels)
- Extract complex logic into separate functions
- Keep functions small and focused
- Use dependency injection where appropriate

### 7. Project Structure Guidelines

```
components/
  ├── ui/              # Pure UI components (buttons, inputs, etc.)
  ├── auth/            # Authentication-specific components
  ├── quran/           # Quran-specific components
  └── layout/          # Layout components

lib/
  ├── utils/           # Pure utility functions
  ├── services/        # Business logic services
  ├── repositories/    # Data access layer
  └── types/           # Type definitions

hooks/                 # Custom React hooks
  ├── useAuth.ts
  ├── useQuran.ts
  └── ...

types/                 # Shared TypeScript types
  ├── user.ts
  ├── quran.ts
  └── ...
```

### 8. Code Quality Standards
- **TypeScript**: Use strict mode, proper typing, avoid `any`
- **Error Handling**: Always handle errors gracefully
- **Naming**: Use descriptive, self-documenting names
- **Comments**: Comment complex logic, not obvious code
- **Imports**: Organize imports (external, internal, relative)
- **Exports**: Use named exports for better tree-shaking

### 9. Component Guidelines
- Keep components small and focused
- Extract logic into custom hooks
- Use composition over inheritance
- Props should be well-typed interfaces
- Avoid prop drilling (use context or state management)
- Separate presentational and container components

### 10. Service Layer Pattern
- Business logic goes in service classes/functions
- Data access goes in repository classes/functions
- Services depend on repositories, not directly on database
- This enables easy testing and future refactoring

### 11. Example: Proper Modular Structure

**BAD** (Monolithic):
```typescript
// ❌ 500+ lines, multiple responsibilities
export function handleUserAndQuranData() { ... }
```

**GOOD** (Modular):
```typescript
// ✅ User service (max 300 lines)
// lib/services/user.service.ts
export class UserService { ... }

// ✅ Quran service (max 300 lines)
// lib/services/quran.service.ts
export class QuranService { ... }

// ✅ User repository (max 300 lines)
// lib/repositories/user.repository.ts
export class UserRepository { ... }
```

### 12. Data Structure Examples

**BAD** (Using array for lookups):
```typescript
// ❌ O(n) lookup time
const users = [{ id: 1, name: 'John' }, ...];
const user = users.find(u => u.id === userId);
```

**GOOD** (Using Map for lookups):
```typescript
// ✅ O(1) lookup time
const usersMap = new Map<number, User>();
usersMap.set(1, { id: 1, name: 'John' });
const user = usersMap.get(userId);
```

### 13. Always Remember
- **Modularity First**: Break things down into smaller, focused pieces
- **SRP**: One responsibility per module/component/function
- **300 Lines Max**: Refactor if exceeded
- **Right Data Structure**: Choose based on use case
- **Create Files First**: Avoid timeout issues
- **Future-Proof**: Write code that's easy to refactor
